description: Medical terms often have a combination of Greek or Latin roots, with the presence of suffixes such as "edema", "osis", "itis", "oma", "emia", and others, frequently denoting medical conditions or diseases.
Medical terms, specifically diseases and related conditions, often represented by a suffix such as -emia, -oma, -osis, or -logy, indicating a condition or study of a particular body part or system.
Suffixes of words related to medical conditions or diseases, such as -osis, -omy, -itis, -ia, -osis, -oma.
Medical terms, procedures, or test names, often related to cancer, often with prefixes and suffixes (e.g., "cyt", "scope", "oma", "pap") and sometimes abbreviated (e.g., "HPV", "PAP", "PSA").
The tokens "er", "oma", and "lymph" are identified as significant in the context of various medical conditions, often related to cancer or disease names, such as melanoma, lymphoma, and carcinoma.
Suffixes and roots related to diseases, particularly cancer, and their characteristics, such as "carcin", "oma", "sarcom", "malign", and "neoplas", as well as terms related to tumors and cells.
Suffixes of medical terms, often indicating a condition, disease, or disorder, such as -itis, -osis, -iasis, -oma, and -asis.
Suffixes or parts of words related to tumors, diseases, or cancer, such as -oma, -macy, or -osis, appear in technical medical language.
Scientific terms and names of organisms, particularly those related to parasites, often have a specific suffix such as "os", "oma", "is", "ode", "z", and "ium".
Suffixes in medical terms, commonly found in words related to disease or conditions, such as -osis, -mat, -oid, and -oma.

Terms related to medical conditions, often suffixes or parts of words referring to types of tumors, cells, or diseases, such as "-oma", "gli", "gi", often in the context of scientific or medical research.

Suffixed forms of words related to cancer, particularly "carcin", "-oma", and "-in" variants (e.g. "carcinogen", "carcinoma", "carcinogenic", and "carcinomas"), as well as standalone words "cancer" and "carcinoma", often in contexts describing the risk, treatment, or research of cancer.

The pattern found in these examples is the presence of suffixes in biological terms, particularly in names of bacteria, diseases, and medical conditions, such as -occus, -pt, -oma, -ella, and -ces, often denoting a specific type or class of organism.
